'''Sin-Kamen''' (Синь-Камень, in [[Russian language|Russian]] literally – '''Blue Stone''', or '''Blue Rock''') is a type of [[pagan]] [[sacred]] [[stone]]s, widespread in [[Russia]] in areas historically inhabited by both [[East Slavic peoples|Eastern Slavic]] ([[Russians|Russian]]), and [[Uralic peoples|Uralic]] tribes ([[Merya]], [[Muroma]]<ref>[http://www.bogorodsk-noginsk.ru/atlas/sinie_kamni.html И.Д. Маланин. Материалы разведки Синих камней Подмосковья в 2003 году // Краеведение и регионоведение. Межвузовский сборник научных трудов. ч.1. Владимир, 2004.] (Russian)</ref>). Unlike [[Sledovik]] (both ''Sledovik'' proper and ''Cup-stones''), ''Blue Stones'' did not have major hallows on them, and were venerated in a simpler way: by pouring [[water]] on them, or leaving food [[Votive offering|offerings]]. Some of the Blue Stones are still known, and to some extent venerated by local populations.
[[File:BlueRock.jpg|thumb|The Sin-Kamen (''Blue Rock'') near [[Lake Pleshcheyevo]] used to be a [[Merya]]n shrine]] If used as a personal name, ''Sin-Kamen'' (Blue Rock) usually refers to the most famous sacred stone of this kind, located on a shore of [[Lake Pleshcheyevo]] near [[Pereslavl-Zalesskiy]]. While in the majority of cases, the stones belonging to the ''Blue Stones'' type are black or dark gray, this particular stone does indeed look dark blue when wet.<ref name="berdnikov">[http://pki.botik.ru/dl.php?b=articles&a=n-sinii1985berd.pdf Бердников,&nbsp;В. Синий камень Плещеева озера]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} // Наука и жизнь. – 1985. – № 1. – С.&nbsp;134–139. (Russian)</ref> The stone surface is covered with small knobs;<ref name="berdnikov" /> its weight is estimated to be about 12 tons.<ref name="komarov">[http://pki.botik.ru/articles/n-sinii2003.pdf Комаров К. И. Древние боги Ярославской земли] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824133619/http://pki.botik.ru/articles/n-sinii2003.pdf |date=August 24, 2011 }} (Russian)</ref> ==See also==
*[[Sami shamanism#Sieidis|Sieidis]] - sacred stones of the Finno-Ugric [[Sami People|Sami]] culture *[[Sledovik]] another type of Slavic/Ugric sacred stone
